i have an older cat with terrible breath i don't know if his teeth are rotting or what but he won't eat those little cat mints sadly i don't have the money to take him to the vet for something so minor but does anyone know what i could do to chill the stink you seriously can smell it across the room this is not a minor problem your cat's dental health can actually affect his whole body it's strange but true there is nothing you can do at home suck it up and get your cat in for a proper dental cleaning after the bacteria and plaque have been removed from under his gum line there are treatments you can use at home to help slow the growth of new bacteria and plaque don't wait until your cat is not able to eat or develops a giant painful abscess in his mouth i've seen it happen too often and it's not good for the cat or the cat's owner ignoring this problem now will cost you more later and subtract years from your kitty's life Dental caries Tooth Tooth enamel Halitosis Oral hygiene Dentistry Domestic rabbit Gingivitis Ferret Oral sex Fancy rat Dental brace Guinea pig Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Traumatic brain injury Fecal incontinence Chronic fatigue syndrome Fluoride therapy Coeliac disease Endocarditis Hydrogen sulfide Raisin Dental floss Foodborne illness Stomach cancer Group A streptococcal infection The Dentist Abscess Garfield AIDS Babe Ruth Bacteria Equine conformation Tuberculosis Toothpaste Psoriasis Common cold Breastfeeding Surgery Mint Multiple sclerosis Decompression sickness Minor Harry Potter Beasts Prostate cancer Richard Chase Medicare (Canada) Medicine Phoebe Buffay's songs Shaggy dog story Pet skunk Diseases of the honeybee Chewing gum Growth hormone treatment Dentures Adolf Hitler's medical health Traditional Chinese medicine First aid Clomipramine Hygiene Gonorrhoea Taboo food and drink Insurance Mesothelioma Fugu Ulcerative colitis Listerine Ragwort Hamster Mosquito Dietary fiber Chocolate Bart chalkboard gags Felis sapiens Diabetes mellitus Bruxism An